That 100 million for Eze was finally put to use.  I wonder if the owners have questioned the manager or they accept that being on top of the table is a good thing even with their biggest investment riding the bench most of the time.

@Al  in Pittsburgh

Aye but Quad dreams still alive! Props to Mansfield.

More Eze, he was such a menace at Crystal Palace. And more Max Dowman, HOLY MOSES! That kid might be the answer to our striker question.

@Jeb Jones
But...there is no swastika, so if one sees it, one IS imagining it.

Do I get my 'NYT Apologist' badge?

@Yael
OK, most of the time the swastikas are in the eye of the beholder and I'm as sensitized to them as anyone can reasonably be.

But this time I see it too. It's in the shape formed by the black squares dotted in the centre, not in the white squares' ground. Of course, it may be an accident or I may be hyper due to recent events here. But the 4 Ls really do seem to be there.

@Patricia Henry
Yeah, I just spent my dinner time on that one, and eventually had to admit google back into my learning experience as well. 

Even Google was of limited help.

@Steve

“Perhaps this dichotomy between slavery and freedom poses too stern a test for our query, are we a nation of laws. Surely it posed a stern test for the very existence of the nation. But was the question of slavery not settled by a Civil War and an amendment to the Constitution barring slavery under state or federal law?”
—A Nation of Laws: America's Imperfect Pursuit of Justice, Peter Charles Hoffer, University Press of Kansas, 2010.

@TCNYC

It's the RECALL that took it off the road. As in, the car has issues and we're doing a recall—taking it off the road. 

It wasn't recalled b/c it could go off-road.

@James

In the US they have one- and two- dollar notes. Hence TWOS are not the lowest denomination note, but are pretty low. 

As for RECALLS, it’s not necessarily a car-specific term, it’s just been clued that way. When some product is found to have a widespread and potentially dangerous fault, the manufacturer might recall it from sale (voluntarily or otherwise)

@Kevin
The question you raise is, who's doing the taking? The clue leaves that open. 
Also, does taking have to mean literally driving? If the dealer lets you know that your car will explode when the odometer hits 12,345 and you wisely decide to have it towed to the dealer, who's taking it off the road?

@Justin
This is what a Saturday is supposed to be like.

It is supposed to be difficult, the clues are supposed to be vague. In short, you have to actually THINK about it. Heaven forbid.

@Sam Lyons

Good to see you back here.  Hope that real life has eased up on its demands and stresses.

We change to daylight saving tonight.  How about you?

@Al  in Pittsburgh
@Sam Lyons
Ditto. Posted a note a day or two ago wondering about your long silence, Sam. Very glad to see you back and hope that whatever it was has worked out for the best.

@Ged
WASH is a common word used in the US, often but not always as dry wash. It refers to exactly what the clue says, a dry stream bed, which are super common in the western US. Sure didn't come to me right away, but I got it easily enough with the crosses.

Sorry that word isn't in your vocabulary, but it is in mine. So "impossible" and "poorly clued" and "clearly" were your experience, not the rest of the world's.

@Nora
You just said it’s a common word in the Western US, it’s not at all common in the rest of the world as you mention at the end.

That’s the rest of the worlds problem though, it’s a New York paper.

@Nancy J.

WAdi slowed me down a lot, too. But I learned it from one of Frank Herbert’s Dune novels. (Herbert throws in a *lot* of Arabic words; there are many references to the Butlerian Jihad, which essentially led to a prohibition on computers.)

And like you, I had to “really work those crosses.” And the challenge was all in the clueing! Of the 72 words in the puzzle, only POCO A POCO is new to me (and I know “poco” as a modifier in musical directions).

@Marshall Walthew

I think that’s why WASH was my first choice. (Also, new season for Dark Winds starring the great Zahn McClarnon.)

But, despite the fact that it was only four letters, my stubborn brain kept wanting it to be arroyo. I guess I’ll blame an MLB ex-pitcher.

@Steve L

As ever, your eyes are as sharp as my hastily-composed comments are sloppy.

Indeed, neither Krone nor Koruna would actually work here.

@Bob
I had confidently put in "radial," as I was seeing a sort of pinwheel.

It's like some sort of mythical beast that has a different appearance based on who's looking at it.

@Katie,

Or maybe the elephant described by the blind men. 

<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blind_men_and_an_elephant" target="_blank">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blind_men_and_an_elephant</a>

@Arthurs

That's simply untrue.  I've read most of them and there are essentially no complaints that the puzzle was too difficult and shouldn't have been used.  People have noted the puzzle was too hard for them and stopped, and others like me observed that the the difficulty level was undone by the lack of joy in the clues and answers.  I only barely skimmed the column and yet got more happiness seeing the constructor thanking his wife than in doing any of his puzzle.

🤷‍♂️

@Jake G

Yah, HOLY. 
Wholly.

@Adrian NW was my streak-breaker! I tried LOANSHARK and MAKOSHARK and even LANDSHARK (oof!) but didn't think of cards. I knew CNOTE wouldn't work but never thought of CSPOT. AND travellers? Duh! Didn't see that one coming!

But the rest was surprisingly satisfying. Difficult, but I managed to figure them out.

Time to start another streak, I guess!

@Adrian

The clue was "Woman central to electioneering?"

IONE forms the *center* of the word, with five letters before and after.

@LStott
Do people not know what DOTTED means?

I am confused by the confusion.

@B

No, relatively few puzzles have patterns where the center is DOTTED with nothing but single, non-contiguous black squares.  That makes it notable if you're analyzing grid design.

Taking recent puzzles as examples, you'll note that Thursday's and Friday's puzzles had a lot of single blocks in the center, but most of them touched others diagonally.  None of the early-week ones had anything resembling this type of structure.  Today's center structure is quite uncommon.

